This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of Natural Language Processing (cs.CL) as it introduces a complementary approach in the field of probabilistic topic modeling. It may also belong to Information Retrieval (cs.IR) as topic modeling is often used in information retrieval tasks. Additionally, it may belong to Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) as it presents a generative model for clustering and optimization. Finally, it may belong to Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) as topic modeling is often used in analyzing social networks.
